  <datafield tag="545" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Intended as a living memorial to former students, faculty, and staff who died in World War II, the Phoenix Project, dedicated to the study of and research on peacetime applications of atomic energy, was created on May 1, 1948, by action of the board of regents.</subfield>
    <subfield code="b">A carefully orchestrated fund-raising campaign headed by President Ruthven raised $8 million within ten years.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="545" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="b">By 1951 substantial research was under way in the study of food preservation, the preservation of metal surfaces, and age determination of pre-historic organic materials. The Phoenix Project germinated exemplary programs at the university in atomic law, atomic medicine, and radiochemistry. Phoenix leadership was instrumental in the founding of the International Cooperation Administration (ICA), an arm of the Atomic Energy Commission (AEC).</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
